1
00:00:03,737 --> 00:00:05,939
What can comfort us more

2
00:00:06,006 --> 00:00:08,975
than a bowl of warm broth

3
00:00:10,710 --> 00:00:12,979
after another long day?

4
00:00:15,181 --> 00:00:17,851
The moment we take a sip,

5
00:00:17,917 --> 00:00:19,986
the furrows in your brow disappear.

6
00:00:20,053 --> 00:00:22,655
Your forehead relaxes
and your lips curl into a smile.

7
00:00:24,124 --> 00:00:27,961
Many Koreans say,
"I can't have a meal without broth."

8
00:00:28,762 --> 00:00:31,564
A typical Korean meal
centers on the bowl of broth.

9
00:00:34,267 --> 00:00:37,137
For us, it's more than
just a bowl of broth.

10
00:00:37,771 --> 00:00:39,973
It gives us comfort and strength.

11
00:00:41,241 --> 00:00:42,942
It's a way of life.

12
00:00:58,892 --> 00:01:02,328
Broth and rice are the basics
of Korean cuisine.

13
00:01:02,395 --> 00:01:04,064
Mixing the two creates gukbap…

14
00:01:04,130 --> 00:01:05,365
HAM YON-JI, ACTRESS

15
00:01:05,432 --> 00:01:08,701
…which is a simple dish
that is inseparable from Koreans.

16
00:01:09,169 --> 00:01:12,138
When you think gukbap,
pork gukbap first comes to mind,

17
00:01:12,205 --> 00:01:14,974
which then reminds you of Busan.

18
00:01:15,041 --> 00:01:19,112
BUSAN

19
00:01:19,179 --> 00:01:20,914
That's why we went to Busan.

20
00:01:24,918 --> 00:01:27,887
Created after the Korean War
this is one of the bigger markets.

21
00:01:27,954 --> 00:01:29,823
It's my first time at Kkangtong Market.

22
00:01:34,427 --> 00:01:36,996
Wherever you go in the world,

23
00:01:37,063 --> 00:01:39,499
markets are good tourist spots.

24
00:01:39,566 --> 00:01:42,969
Markets are filled with liveliness.
I feel the energy of the place.

25
00:01:43,036 --> 00:01:44,370
TRADITIONAL MARKET
BUSTLING WITH ENERGY

26
00:01:48,441 --> 00:01:49,275
It's good.

27
00:01:49,342 --> 00:01:50,710
Busan odeng is the best.

28
00:01:52,545 --> 00:01:53,847
It sure is good.

29
00:01:54,814 --> 00:01:57,150
-I had this when I was a student.
-Right.

30
00:01:57,217 --> 00:01:58,852
I remember my student days too.

31
00:01:59,486 --> 00:02:00,453
Is it there, sir?

32
00:02:00,520 --> 00:02:01,354
Here.

33
00:02:01,421 --> 00:02:02,522
So it's this house.

34
00:02:02,589 --> 00:02:03,656
Just by the corner.

35
00:02:03,723 --> 00:02:04,691
It's really big.

36
00:02:04,757 --> 00:02:06,359
-Hello.
-It's at the market entryway.

37
00:02:07,026 --> 00:02:09,362
There's pyeonyuk by the entrance.

38
00:02:09,429 --> 00:02:10,430
-Hello.
-Hello.

39
00:02:10,497 --> 00:02:11,698
Hello.

40
00:02:11,764 --> 00:02:12,932
She's pouring broth.

41
00:02:12,999 --> 00:02:14,467
That's amazing.

42
00:02:14,534 --> 00:02:17,704
Hello. You're actually using
the toryeom technique.

43
00:02:17,770 --> 00:02:20,273
TORYEOM, THE REGULAR APPLICATION
OF HOT BROTH ON RICE TO HEAT IT

44
00:02:20,874 --> 00:02:22,142
Your wrist must hurt.

45
00:02:22,208 --> 00:02:23,676
How long have you done this?

46
00:02:23,743 --> 00:02:24,944
So much meat.

47
00:02:25,011 --> 00:02:27,247
Over 20 years, maybe 25 years.

48
00:02:27,313 --> 00:02:28,448
That's amazing.

49
00:02:31,684 --> 00:02:36,022
A GUKBAP HOUSE THAT SHOWS
TRACES OF ITS 25 YEARS

50
00:02:38,925 --> 00:02:40,426
I'm excited for the food.

51
00:02:40,493 --> 00:02:41,728
The aroma…

52
00:02:42,162 --> 00:02:48,301
PORK GUKBAP

53
00:02:48,368 --> 00:02:49,402
Hello.

54
00:02:49,469 --> 00:02:50,303
Hi.

55
00:02:50,370 --> 00:02:51,437
You're so beautiful.

56
00:02:51,504 --> 00:02:52,739
JEONG JEONG-A, OWNER OF
A PORK GUKBAP HOUSE OF 54 YEARS

57
00:02:52,805 --> 00:02:53,806
-Hello.
-Yes, hello.

58
00:02:53,873 --> 00:02:55,008
I want pork gukbap.

59
00:02:55,074 --> 00:02:55,975
-Me too.
-Okay.

60
00:02:56,042 --> 00:02:57,710
-The mixed dish for me.
-All right.

61
00:02:57,777 --> 00:02:59,612
Should I have pyeonyuk or suyuk?

62
00:02:59,679 --> 00:03:00,580
How do they differ?

63
00:03:00,647 --> 00:03:03,082
-Half-and-half, please.
-All right.

64
00:03:03,149 --> 00:03:04,551
Oh, that's it.

65
00:03:05,618 --> 00:03:07,420
How long has this place been here?

66
00:03:07,487 --> 00:03:11,791
My parents started this place.
So it's been over 50 years.

67
00:03:11,858 --> 00:03:13,726
You're the veteran of this market.

68
00:03:13,793 --> 00:03:15,128
That's right.

69
00:03:15,195 --> 00:03:18,164
You've been in this spot for 50 years?

70
00:03:18,231 --> 00:03:19,832
Yes, right here.

71
00:03:19,899 --> 00:03:21,501
Wow, amazing.

72
00:03:21,568 --> 00:03:24,037
4:00 A.M.

73
00:03:24,938 --> 00:03:26,940
Every day at dawn,

74
00:03:27,006 --> 00:03:29,008
we trim the meat

75
00:03:29,075 --> 00:03:30,643
that we bring from the farm.

76
00:03:31,444 --> 00:03:34,914
We start with the leg bones and the head

77
00:03:34,981 --> 00:03:36,749
and boil it the old-fashioned way.

78
00:03:37,217 --> 00:03:40,887
About 15, 16 pigs fit into one pot

79
00:03:40,954 --> 00:03:42,655
so we use three pots.

80
00:03:42,722 --> 00:03:45,091
Meaning, around 50 pigs.

81
00:03:45,158 --> 00:03:47,160
Then we repeat the process.

82
00:03:47,227 --> 00:03:48,828
So 100 pigs in total.

83
00:03:51,397 --> 00:03:55,868
A HUNDRED PIG HEADS
IN A DAY'S WORTH OF BROTH

84
00:03:56,569 --> 00:03:57,971
Look over there, sir.

85
00:03:58,037 --> 00:03:59,205
-Pig heads.
-Yes.

86
00:03:59,272 --> 00:04:01,007
-I've never seen this.
-Me either.

87
00:04:03,243 --> 00:04:06,446
I hear that if you boil
then dry the pig heads

88
00:04:06,512 --> 00:04:08,214
its texture changes.

89
00:04:08,281 --> 00:04:11,317
DRYING BOILED PIG HEADS
FOR ONE HOUR

90
00:04:12,685 --> 00:04:14,687
-I heard something too.
-What's that?

91
00:04:14,754 --> 00:04:18,825
That Busan locals have pork gukbap broth
coursing through their veins.

92
00:04:18,891 --> 00:04:20,860
-I heard that.
-They really love this dish.

93
00:04:20,927 --> 00:04:24,330
If you ask Busan locals,
"What should I eat in Busan?"

94
00:04:24,397 --> 00:04:26,132
-"Pork gukbap."
-Correct.

95
00:04:26,199 --> 00:04:29,002
This morning, I went to one
of the public bathhouses here.

96
00:04:29,068 --> 00:04:32,438
Someone over there
was telling me about pork gukbap.

97
00:04:32,505 --> 00:04:34,540
The locals have specific preferences.

98
00:04:34,607 --> 00:04:38,044
So some places use chicken feet,
some only use pork,

99
00:04:38,111 --> 00:04:40,413
some use only bones, and others use beef.

100
00:04:40,480 --> 00:04:42,248
They all use different stock.

101
00:04:42,315 --> 00:04:44,317
But locals have
their personal preferences.

102
00:04:44,384 --> 00:04:48,554
Apparently, there are
around 300 kinds of gukbap.

103
00:04:48,621 --> 00:04:50,790
-300?
-Pork gukbap?

104
00:04:50,857 --> 00:04:52,425
I looked it up online

105
00:04:53,026 --> 00:04:56,129
and there are 700 pork gukbap places
in Busan.

106
00:04:56,195 --> 00:05:00,500
If that's true, there's a pork gukbap
place every 1.1 kilometer.

107
00:05:01,034 --> 00:05:02,769
-Every 1.1 kilometer?
-Yes.

108
00:05:02,835 --> 00:05:05,405
-That's the number of cafés in Seoul.
-You're right.

109
00:05:06,239 --> 00:05:08,408
SOMUNNAN PIG GUKBAP
BONJEON PIG GUKBAP

110
00:05:08,474 --> 00:05:09,475
BUSAN PIG GUKBAP

111
00:05:16,849 --> 00:05:18,151
I'm almost done.

112
00:05:18,217 --> 00:05:19,686
Maybe one more minute?

113
00:05:20,787 --> 00:05:23,756
I'm pretty good with timing.

114
00:05:23,823 --> 00:05:27,894
When I boil meat, I want it to be tender

115
00:05:29,796 --> 00:05:32,065
and hot enough for a ttukbaegi bowl.

116
00:05:32,131 --> 00:05:33,499
That's when I serve it up.

117
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,170
You get a feel for it
when you do this every day.

118
00:05:37,236 --> 00:05:39,806
You need to have a sense for it.

119
00:05:42,408 --> 00:05:46,212
BUSAN STYLE PIG GUKBAP

120
00:05:46,813 --> 00:05:47,647
It's here.

121
00:05:47,714 --> 00:05:49,215
It's presented beautifully.

122
00:05:49,282 --> 00:05:50,583
It's so pretty.

123
00:05:50,650 --> 00:05:52,852
You add unseasoned chives here?

124
00:05:52,919 --> 00:05:54,287
-Yes.
-So that's why.

125
00:05:54,787 --> 00:05:55,621
Hope you enjoy.

126
00:05:55,688 --> 00:05:56,956
-Yes.
-Thank you.

127
00:05:57,023 --> 00:05:58,958
The man at the bathhouse suggested…

128
00:05:59,025 --> 00:06:00,426
BY HUH YOUNG-MAN

129
00:06:00,493 --> 00:06:03,363
…that I don't mix the sauce with the broth
before taking the first sip.

130
00:06:03,429 --> 00:06:05,064
So don't mix the sauce yet?

131
00:06:05,131 --> 00:06:06,833
-Taste the broth first.
-Correct.

132
00:06:10,837 --> 00:06:11,838
That's so good.

133
00:06:11,904 --> 00:06:13,606
-It's good.
-Right?

134
00:06:13,673 --> 00:06:15,174
-Like baeksuk, huh?
-Exactly.

135
00:06:15,241 --> 00:06:16,809
You wouldn't know without looking.

136
00:06:16,876 --> 00:06:18,878
-I agree.
-It's like chicken baeksuk.

137
00:06:18,945 --> 00:06:19,979
-Yum.
-It's so good.

138
00:06:20,046 --> 00:06:21,447
BROTH WITH A CLEAN TASTE
LIKE CHICKEN BAEKSUK

139
00:06:21,914 --> 00:06:25,685
The ear is fatty and chewy but flavorful.

140
00:06:25,752 --> 00:06:26,886
EAR MEAT

141
00:06:26,953 --> 00:06:29,655
The tongue meat is all lean meat…

142
00:06:29,722 --> 00:06:30,723
JEONG JEONG-A, OWNER OF A PORK
GUKBAP HOUSE OF 54 YEARS

143
00:06:30,790 --> 00:06:32,058
…so it has a light taste.

144
00:06:32,658 --> 00:06:35,128
The cheek area is chewy

145
00:06:35,194 --> 00:06:37,964
but oily because there's some fat there.

146
00:06:38,598 --> 00:06:41,167
The nose feels like
you're chewing on collagen.

147
00:06:41,234 --> 00:06:43,069
It's very chewy.

148
00:06:48,875 --> 00:06:50,977
You think this would be good with soju?

149
00:06:52,211 --> 00:06:53,946
I wasn't going to say anything.

150
00:06:55,782 --> 00:06:58,151
-One bottle of soju, please.
-This early?

151
00:06:58,217 --> 00:06:59,852
Soju is a morning drink.

152
00:07:02,455 --> 00:07:03,523
Yes, Busan.

153
00:07:03,589 --> 00:07:04,857
Busan!

154
00:07:04,924 --> 00:07:07,627
-It's a crime not to drink with this.
-I agree.

155
00:07:07,693 --> 00:07:08,828
It's a serious mistake.

156
00:07:08,895 --> 00:07:11,264
This dish calls for at least one bottle.

157
00:07:20,840 --> 00:07:26,412
A DISH THAT'S EVEN TASTIER
WITH DRINKS

158
00:07:28,614 --> 00:07:31,217
Soju tastes sweet with this broth.
Oh, dear.

159
00:07:32,919 --> 00:07:34,320
Suyuk is served.

160
00:07:34,387 --> 00:07:36,155
This much is a half portion?

161
00:07:36,222 --> 00:07:37,924
Which is the tongue meat?

162
00:07:37,990 --> 00:07:39,158
It's here.

163
00:07:39,225 --> 00:07:40,259
PORK SUYUK PLATTER

164
00:07:40,326 --> 00:07:43,362
This here, is the cheek meat.

165
00:07:43,429 --> 00:07:44,530
-One question.
-Sure.

166
00:07:45,298 --> 00:07:47,667
-Can I order more broth?
-Of course.

167
00:07:48,801 --> 00:07:50,870
Apologies, he eats a lot sometimes.

168
00:07:50,937 --> 00:07:52,738
He usually doesn't eat this much.

169
00:07:52,805 --> 00:07:54,440
This isn't like him.

170
00:07:55,975 --> 00:07:57,610
Let's try the cheek meat.

171
00:07:58,611 --> 00:08:00,112
This is expensive meat.

172
00:08:00,179 --> 00:08:02,181
You know pasta carbonara?

173
00:08:02,248 --> 00:08:05,017
Italians make carbonara
with pork cheek meat.

174
00:08:05,084 --> 00:08:06,486
They use ham made from this.

175
00:08:06,552 --> 00:08:07,920
It's called guanciale.

176
00:08:07,987 --> 00:08:09,655
It's a very flavorful area.

177
00:08:20,833 --> 00:08:22,535
The more you chew…

178
00:08:22,602 --> 00:08:24,504
AN EXPLOSION OF TASTE
PORK CHEEK MEAT

179
00:08:24,570 --> 00:08:25,671
Even the fat is tasty.

180
00:08:25,738 --> 00:08:27,406
Here's a reason to live a long life.

181
00:08:27,473 --> 00:08:29,108
What's that?

182
00:08:29,542 --> 00:08:31,577
There's so much to eat.

183
00:08:34,313 --> 00:08:35,681
This is so good.

184
00:08:35,748 --> 00:08:37,116
The cheek meat.

185
00:08:39,552 --> 00:08:42,154
I always think in metaphors.

186
00:08:42,221 --> 00:08:44,357
Seolleongtang and gomtang
are like asphalt.

187
00:08:45,124 --> 00:08:46,225
This is an unpaved road.

188
00:08:46,692 --> 00:08:48,261
It's unrefined,

189
00:08:48,327 --> 00:08:51,731
but it represents the tastebuds
of the locals.

190
00:08:52,431 --> 00:08:55,234
That's how I described it in my cartoon.

191
00:08:55,301 --> 00:08:56,903
-In Sikgaek.
-I remember it.

192
00:08:56,969 --> 00:08:59,138
"Like a young rebel speeding
on an unpaved road."

193
00:08:59,205 --> 00:09:00,206
Yes, a young rebel.

194
00:09:00,273 --> 00:09:02,108
"THE TASTE OF A YOUNG REBEL
SPEEDING ON AN UNPAVED ROAD", FROM SIKGAEK

195
00:09:02,174 --> 00:09:03,743
You have many regulars?

196
00:09:04,210 --> 00:09:05,144
Yes, of course.

197
00:09:05,211 --> 00:09:08,581
People miss their mother's
home cooking, made with love,

198
00:09:08,648 --> 00:09:11,317
and some people still come
and tell me that.

199
00:09:11,384 --> 00:09:12,351
The merchants here.

200
00:09:12,418 --> 00:09:14,353
THE ONE SATISFYING MEAL
FOR BUSY MERCHANTS

201
00:09:14,420 --> 00:09:15,888
Our regulars consist

202
00:09:16,322 --> 00:09:18,391
of merchants in the vicinity

203
00:09:18,457 --> 00:09:20,226
and delivery people.

204
00:09:23,462 --> 00:09:26,499
During difficult times in the past,

205
00:09:26,566 --> 00:09:30,603
this was the one hot bowl
they could eat until they were full.

206
00:09:30,670 --> 00:09:31,704
Plus, it was cheap.

207
00:09:32,238 --> 00:09:34,707
After a tiring day of work,

208
00:09:34,774 --> 00:09:37,109
they'd come here at the end of the day

209
00:09:37,176 --> 00:09:40,179
and have a hot bowl of gukbap.

210
00:09:40,246 --> 00:09:42,248
"A gukbap bowl of happiness."

211
00:09:42,315 --> 00:09:44,350
That's what they say.

212
00:09:47,553 --> 00:09:50,890
The reason pork gukbap
is adored by Busan locals

213
00:09:51,424 --> 00:09:54,260
is because it warms the soul.

214
00:09:54,860 --> 00:09:57,096
How comforting it must be.

215
00:09:59,298 --> 00:10:03,569
DAEGU

216
00:10:05,471 --> 00:10:06,739
This is Daegu!

217
00:10:07,206 --> 00:10:09,542
I think it's warmer here than Busan.

218
00:10:09,609 --> 00:10:12,311
Daegu is famous for its hot weather.

219
00:10:12,378 --> 00:10:15,281
-Geographically, Daegu is a basin.
-They call it "Daefrica."

220
00:10:17,049 --> 00:10:18,784
Since the Joseon Era,

221
00:10:18,851 --> 00:10:21,587
Daegu's cattle market was always
well-developed.

222
00:10:21,654 --> 00:10:24,423
They have something called mungtigi,

223
00:10:24,490 --> 00:10:26,225
a dish made with only fresh meat.

224
00:10:28,160 --> 00:10:29,328
They also have jjimgalbi.

225
00:10:29,395 --> 00:10:31,998
It's a very spicy dish.
A quite famous one.

226
00:10:32,064 --> 00:10:33,065
SPICY GALBIJJIM

227
00:10:33,132 --> 00:10:37,470
The city of Daegu is a basin.
It gets very hot and very cold.

228
00:10:37,536 --> 00:10:39,705
So, the weather affects their cuisine.

229
00:10:39,772 --> 00:10:43,509
DAEGU, THE HOLY LAND
OF BEEF DISHES

230
00:10:43,576 --> 00:10:44,910
-Is it here?
-Yes.

231
00:10:44,977 --> 00:10:47,413
Recently in Daegu,
makchang has become popular.

232
00:10:47,480 --> 00:10:49,782
-Right.
-Daegu is known for yukgaejang.

233
00:10:49,849 --> 00:10:50,816
-We're here.
-Hello.

234
00:10:50,883 --> 00:10:52,251
-Welcome in.
-Hello.

235
00:10:54,253 --> 00:10:55,454
YUKGAEJANG - 8,500 WON

236
00:10:55,521 --> 00:10:57,390
Yukgaejang is your signature dish?

237
00:10:57,456 --> 00:10:58,290
-Right?
-Yes.

238
00:10:58,357 --> 00:11:00,259
-Yukguksu sounds good.
-Yukguksu.

239
00:11:00,326 --> 00:11:02,595
Instead of rice in yukgaejang

240
00:11:02,662 --> 00:11:04,130
it comes with noodles.

241
00:11:04,196 --> 00:11:05,398
It's also good.

242
00:11:08,567 --> 00:11:10,136
-We'll have yukgaejang.
-Yes.

243
00:11:10,202 --> 00:11:11,704
Three orders of yukgaejang then?

244
00:11:12,772 --> 00:11:16,208
You mentioned yukgaejang places
are disappearing in Seoul.

245
00:11:16,275 --> 00:11:18,444
I just can't seem to find one in Seoul.

246
00:11:18,511 --> 00:11:20,513
Probably because a lot of effort

247
00:11:20,579 --> 00:11:22,181
goes into making yukgaejang.

248
00:11:22,715 --> 00:11:25,317
Do you think that's the reason?

249
00:11:25,384 --> 00:11:28,087
I reckon it was a very famous soup.

250
00:11:28,154 --> 00:11:30,122
This cookbook
is from the early 20th century.

251
00:11:30,189 --> 00:11:32,591
-Yes.
-The first edition of how to make soup…

252
00:11:32,658 --> 00:11:33,659
Yes.

253
00:11:33,726 --> 00:11:34,727
…has yukgaejang.

254
00:11:35,728 --> 00:11:36,829
Here.

255
00:11:36,896 --> 00:11:38,864
It's on the first page.

256
00:11:38,931 --> 00:11:41,300
Next is gomguk, then mixed seafood stew.

257
00:11:41,367 --> 00:11:42,635
Then fish stew.

258
00:11:42,702 --> 00:11:44,637
The knee, crucible, beef rib,

259
00:11:44,704 --> 00:11:47,273
