00:46:02,226 --> 00:46:05,062
SEOLLEONGTANG

1019
00:46:05,129 --> 00:46:06,730
It looks good.

1020
00:46:08,499 --> 00:46:09,767
There's so much meat.

1021
00:46:09,833 --> 00:46:10,667
It's heavy.

1022
00:46:12,970 --> 00:46:14,671
The way it's presented is beautiful.

1023
00:46:26,817 --> 00:46:29,119
This bowl is on another plane.

1024
00:46:29,186 --> 00:46:30,254
It's so different.

1025
00:46:30,721 --> 00:46:32,322
Seolleongtang comes from Seoul.

1026
00:46:32,389 --> 00:46:34,525
"Seoul noblemen are picky."

1027
00:46:34,591 --> 00:46:37,327
I think that phrase
could've started with this.

1028
00:46:37,961 --> 00:46:39,329
The broth.

1029
00:46:39,396 --> 00:46:40,497
The meat.

1030
00:46:40,964 --> 00:46:41,932
Even the kimchi.

1031
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:46,170
Everything is up to par. It's perfect.

1032
00:46:46,236 --> 00:46:47,070
I agree.

1033
00:46:47,137 --> 00:46:49,106
They would've had this since the past.

1034
00:46:49,573 --> 00:46:51,441
Noblemen sure have good taste.

1035
00:46:53,744 --> 00:46:57,548
NOODLES ARE A MUST FOR SEOLLEONGTANG

1036
00:46:58,649 --> 00:47:00,317
Sir, the noodles are plentiful.

1037
00:47:00,384 --> 00:47:02,152
I've never seen this much in here.

1038
00:47:02,219 --> 00:47:03,587
Right, they add so little.

1039
00:47:03,654 --> 00:47:06,390
-Some people only want noodles, no rice.
-Right?

1040
00:47:06,456 --> 00:47:07,691
It's a noodle stew.

1041
00:47:12,496 --> 00:47:14,431
The noodles are seasoned.

1042
00:47:15,065 --> 00:47:17,568
-Noodles are made along with salt.
-I see.

1043
00:47:18,936 --> 00:47:22,306
A SATISFYING TASTE

1044
00:47:27,678 --> 00:47:29,012
Do you want kkakdugi water?

1045
00:47:29,079 --> 00:47:30,047
The water.

1046
00:47:30,514 --> 00:47:32,115
Sir, can we have kkakdugi juice?

1047
00:47:32,182 --> 00:47:34,384
Kkakdugi juice.

1048
00:47:34,451 --> 00:47:35,352
Cuckoo.

1049
00:47:35,419 --> 00:47:37,387
-Cuckoo.
-Cuckoo.

1050
00:47:37,454 --> 00:47:39,656
THE HIGHLIGHT OF SEOLLEONGTANG
THE KKAKDUGI JUICE

1051
00:47:39,723 --> 00:47:41,024
How many spoons?

1052
00:47:41,091 --> 00:47:42,593
-Trust me.
-All right.

1053
00:47:42,659 --> 00:47:45,596
I'm adding this
because I know its original taste.

1054
00:47:45,662 --> 00:47:47,231
THE SWEET, SPICY AND REFRESHING
KKAKDUGI JUICE

1055
00:47:47,297 --> 00:47:48,932
I wanted to see how it would change.

1056
00:47:57,241 --> 00:47:58,442
I think I failed.

1057
00:48:00,878 --> 00:48:02,546
Why? The sour taste is good.

1058
00:48:02,613 --> 00:48:04,281
I find this charming too.

1059
00:48:04,348 --> 00:48:08,352
What's the difference between
seolleongtang and gomtang?

1060
00:48:08,418 --> 00:48:09,286
Seolleongtang…

1061
00:48:09,353 --> 00:48:10,420
CURIOUS

1062
00:48:10,487 --> 00:48:12,022
…is boiled casually.

1063
00:48:13,357 --> 00:48:15,192
Then gomtang is boiled carefully?

1064
00:48:15,926 --> 00:48:17,461
Gomtang is boiled carefully.

1065
00:48:17,527 --> 00:48:18,862
Carefully.

1066
00:48:18,929 --> 00:48:19,963
How carefully?

1067
00:48:20,430 --> 00:48:22,633
According to what I've read,

1068
00:48:22,699 --> 00:48:25,302
the most accurate to tell
the difference is this.

1069
00:48:25,369 --> 00:48:27,938
If beef leg bones are used,
then it's a seolleongtang.

1070
00:48:28,005 --> 00:48:29,273
SEOLLEONGTANG USES THE BONES

1071
00:48:30,173 --> 00:48:32,843
If the broth is made with meat,
then it's a gomtang.

1072
00:48:32,910 --> 00:48:34,177
GOMTANG USES THE MEAT

1073
00:48:36,947 --> 00:48:40,817
100 years ago, weren't there
100 seolleongtang places?

1074
00:48:40,884 --> 00:48:44,588
Every vicinity had slaughterhouses.

1075
00:48:44,655 --> 00:48:49,626
When they caught anything,
the nobles only ate the meat.

1076
00:48:49,693 --> 00:48:53,263
Whereas the remainder,
like the bones, they didn't eat.

1077
00:48:53,330 --> 00:48:58,268
So, they were given as payment
to those who slaughtered the animal.

1078
00:48:59,303 --> 00:49:00,437
Then what?

1079
00:49:00,504 --> 00:49:04,374
They needed to make money,
not receive more meat.

1080
00:49:04,441 --> 00:49:09,913
That's why they developed
seolleongtang and gomtang.

1081
00:49:10,914 --> 00:49:12,649
We came all the way to Seoul station.

1082
00:49:12,716 --> 00:49:15,452
-Let's have one more thing.
-Sure.

1083
00:49:15,519 --> 00:49:16,520
One dogani-tang.

1084
00:49:16,586 --> 00:49:17,421
-Dogani-tang?
-Yes.

1085
00:49:18,689 --> 00:49:21,191
This is made with
knee cartilage and tendons.

1086
00:49:21,892 --> 00:49:25,996
We boil it for about an hour.
If the meat is tough, we boil again.

1087
00:49:31,802 --> 00:49:32,903
Oh, it's soft.

1088
00:49:33,370 --> 00:49:34,838
We have to add something.

1089
00:49:34,905 --> 00:49:37,074
Collagen calls for some alcohol.

1090
00:49:37,140 --> 00:49:39,376
To cleanse the oiliness in your mouth.

1091
00:49:39,443 --> 00:49:40,477
GIVE

1092
00:49:40,544 --> 00:49:41,712
AND TAKE

1093
00:49:41,778 --> 00:49:43,113
One bottle of soju, please.

1094
00:49:44,448 --> 00:49:46,049
You need one glass of this.

1095
00:49:46,116 --> 00:49:47,617
After you had a salty spoonful,

1096
00:49:48,719 --> 00:49:51,088
you cleanse your palette with soju.

1097
00:49:51,154 --> 00:49:53,190
If it gets salty again, another shot.

1098
00:50:03,133 --> 00:50:04,668
Gomtang was a nobleman's dish.

1099
00:50:04,735 --> 00:50:05,969
Yeah, it was for noblemen.

1100
00:50:06,036 --> 00:50:08,772
Seolleongtang was for commoners.

1101
00:50:08,839 --> 00:50:12,376
It grew with the joys and sorrows
of commoners.

1102
00:50:13,010 --> 00:50:14,945
That's its charm.

1103
00:50:15,012 --> 00:50:19,182
When I think seolleongtang,
I think of franchises.

1104
00:50:19,249 --> 00:50:22,652
That's why I think it has survived well

1105
00:50:22,719 --> 00:50:26,723
and adapted to the times better
than all Korean dishes.

1106
00:50:27,224 --> 00:50:28,859
That's my opinion.

1107
00:50:28,925 --> 00:50:30,060
Seolleongtang, galbitang?

1108
00:50:30,127 --> 00:50:31,361
-Seolleongtang.
-Me, too.

1109
00:50:31,428 --> 00:50:32,596
Me, too.

1110
00:50:32,662 --> 00:50:34,731
-It's a heartier dish.
-Yes.

1111
00:50:34,798 --> 00:50:36,700
-I love the milky broth.
-Yes.

1112
00:50:36,767 --> 00:50:38,668
SEOLLEONGTANG, THE ONE BOWL
KOREANS LOVE MOST

1113
00:50:39,302 --> 00:50:42,906
WHAT IS BROTH TO KOREANS?

1114
00:50:42,973 --> 00:50:45,742
Broth has comforted

1115
00:50:45,809 --> 00:50:50,313
and strengthened our nation
for a long time.

1116
00:50:50,380 --> 00:50:52,516
A meal without broth

1117
00:50:52,582 --> 00:50:54,818
is unimaginable to us.

1118
00:50:54,885 --> 00:50:57,687
The rice in broth tradition
courses through our blood.

1119
00:50:57,754 --> 00:51:00,357
It's a part of our culture.

1120
00:51:00,824 --> 00:51:03,226
We have broth when we're
in our mother's womb.

1121
00:51:04,027 --> 00:51:08,298
A pregnant mother eats seaweed soup

1122
00:51:08,365 --> 00:51:09,566
to nurture her child.

1123
00:51:10,067 --> 00:51:11,868
Even on good occasions,

1124
00:51:12,369 --> 00:51:13,437
like for weddings,

1125
00:51:14,071 --> 00:51:17,107
you spread goodwill with galbitang.

1126
00:51:17,174 --> 00:51:20,177
"When are you buying galbitang?
When are you making noodles?"

1127
00:51:20,243 --> 00:51:24,047
These sayings exist for a reason.
We spread generosity with soup.

1128
00:51:24,881 --> 00:51:27,551
We serve yukgaejang
upon someone's passing.

1129
00:51:28,485 --> 00:51:32,456
This shows how from before birth
and until after death

1130
00:51:32,522 --> 00:51:36,893
and every moment in between,
broth is always by our side.

1131
00:51:37,360 --> 00:51:40,497
To Koreans, broth is a way of life.

1132
00:51:40,564 --> 00:51:41,865
That's what I think.

1133
00:51:42,699 --> 00:51:48,071
BROTH WILL BE WITH US
IN EVERY MOMENT OF OUR LIVES

1134
00:52:13,964 --> 00:52:18,969
